00:00:00.540 --> 00:00:02.150
- [Instructor] In this video,
we're gonna do a couple

00:00:02.150 --> 00:00:06.320
of examples that deal with
parallel and perpendicular lines.

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:08.850
So you have parallel,

00:00:08.850 --> 00:00:12.138
you have perpendicular,

00:00:12.138 --> 00:00:15.412
and of course you have lines
that are neither parallel

00:00:15.412 --> 00:00:17.100
nor perpendicular.

00:00:17.100 --> 00:00:18.340
And just as a bit of a review,

00:00:18.340 --> 00:00:19.990
if you've never seen this before,

00:00:19.990 --> 00:00:22.640
parallel lines they never intersect.

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:25.300
So let me draw some axes.

00:00:25.300 --> 00:00:27.570
So if those are my
coordinate axes right there,

00:00:27.570 --> 00:00:31.530
it's my X-axis, that is my Y-axis,

00:00:31.530 --> 00:00:34.530
if this is a line that
I'm drawing in magenta,

00:00:34.530 --> 00:00:38.600
a parallel line might
look something like this.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:40.420
It's not the exact same line,

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:42.720
but they have the exact same slope.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:44.458
If this moves a certain amount,

00:00:44.458 --> 00:00:47.770
if this change in Y over
change in X is a certain amount

00:00:47.770 --> 00:00:51.140
this change change in Y over
change in X is the same amount.

00:00:51.140 --> 00:00:53.750
And that's why they never intersect.

00:00:53.750 --> 00:00:58.750
So they have the same slope.

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:01.490
Parallel lines have the same slope.

00:01:01.490 --> 00:01:04.130
Perpendicular lines, depending
on how you wanna view it,

00:01:04.130 --> 00:01:06.253
they're kind of the opposite.

00:01:06.253 --> 00:01:10.200
Let's say this is some line,
a line that is perpendicular

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:13.240
to that, will not only intersect the line,

00:01:13.240 --> 00:01:14.810
it won't only intersect the line,

00:01:14.810 --> 00:01:17.470
it will intersect it at a right angle.

00:01:17.470 --> 00:01:19.450
At a 90 degree angle.

00:01:19.450 --> 00:01:22.730
At a 90 degree angle, and
I'm not going to prove it

00:01:22.730 --> 00:01:24.270
for you here, I actually prove it

00:01:24.270 --> 00:01:25.900
in the linear algebra playlist,

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:28.470
but a perpendicular lined slope,

00:01:28.470 --> 00:01:31.750
let's say this one right here,
let's say that yellow line

00:01:31.750 --> 00:01:35.560
has a slope of M, then this orange line

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:37.690
that's perpendicular to the yellow line

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:42.120
is going to have a slope
of negative one over M.

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:44.936
Their slopes are gonna
be the negative inverse

00:01:44.936 --> 00:01:46.810
of each other.

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:48.790
Now, given this information,

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:51.140
let's look at a bunch
of lines and figure out

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:53.660
if they're parallel, if
they're perpendicular,

00:01:53.660 --> 00:01:55.140
or if they are neither.

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:58.700
And to do that, we just have
to keep looking at the slopes.

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:00.710
So let's see, they say
one line passes through

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:03.350
the points four and negative three

00:02:03.350 --> 00:02:05.470
and negative eight, zero.

